'''Cape Verdean Cuban''' are [[Cuba]]n citizens or residents whose ancestry originated in [[Cape Verde]].

[[Cape Verde]] and [[Cuba]] have had a long history. The first people from Cape Verde to Cuba came involuntarily. In 1526, the "first known shipment of slaves intended for sale in [[Cuba]] carries 145 Africans from [[Cape Verde|Cabo Verde]] to the island."<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/buenavista/music/timeline.html Ron Conner, "Timeline of Cuban Musical History." PBS. Retrieved October 26, 2006.]</ref> More slaves from [[Cape Verde]] would follow. This would include the ancestor of [[Roel Caboverde Llacer]], a famous Cuban artist.<ref>[http://www.cubanartstore.com/caboverde.htm Reinaldo Cedeño Pineda, " Roel Caboverde Llacer - Interview." Cuban Art Store. Retrieved October 26, 2006.]</ref>

[[Cuba]] and [[Cape Verde]] established diplomatic relations in September 1975, a few months after Cape Verdean independence. "Since 1976, over 1,000 Cuban collaborators, mostly physicians and health technicians, have been working in that African nation, and nearly 1,000 Cape Verdean scholarship students have completed pre-university and university studies in Cuba."<ref name=Castro>[http://www.cubaminrex.cu/english/currentissues/2005/Fidel%20Castro%20Decorates.htm "Fidel Castro Decorates Cape Verde´s President." Cuba Mix Rex.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021112930/http://www.cubaminrex.cu/english/currentissues/2005/Fidel%20Castro%20Decorates.htm |date=October 21, 2007 }}</ref> As of 2007, however, there are no estimates for the number of people of Cape Verdean descent living in [[Cuba]].

In 2005, [[Germano Almeida|Germano Almeida's]] ''Two Brothers'' was translated into Spanish and included in an ''Arts and Literature'' anthology.<ref>[https://archive.is/20070528163214/http://www.clacso.org.ar/difusion/secciones/programa-de-cooperacion-sur-sur/Descargables/ceamonitor-ago-2006_archivos.htm David González, "Nueva literatura caboverdiana en Cuba." Envío CEAMOnitor Vol 3 No 7. Retrieved October 26, 2006.] (In Spanish)</ref> In the same year, [[Fidel Castro]] presented [[Pedro Pires|Pedro Rodrigues Pires]] with the Jose Marti Order, Cuba's highest decoration.<ref name=Castro/>

