{{Infobox language |name=Deilami |nativename= {{lang|fa|ديلمی}} |states=[[Iran]] |region=South [[Caspian Sea]], [[Alborz]] highlands |familycolor=Indo-European |era=900–1300AD |ref=<ref>Mehdi Marashi, Mohammad Ali Jazayery, Persian studies in North America: studies in honor of Mohammad Ali Jazayery, Ibex Publishers, Inc., 1994, {{ISBN|0-936347-35-X}}, 9780936347356, p. 269</ref> |fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] |fam3=[[Iranian languages|Iranian]] |fam4=[[Western Iranian languages|Western Iranian]] |fam5=[[Caspian languages|Caspian]] |script= [[Persian alphabet]] |iso3=none |glotto=none }}
The '''Daylami language''', also known as ''Daylamite'', ''Deilami'', ''Dailamite'', or ''Deylami'' (Deilami: {{lang|fa|دیلمی}}, from the name of the [[Daylam]] region), is an [[extinct language]] that was one of the northwestern branch of the [[Iranian languages]]. It was spoken in northern [[Iran]], specifically in the mountainous area in [[Gilan Province|Gīlān]], [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]], and [[Qazvin Province|Ghazvin]] Provinces.
[[Parviz Natel Khanlari]] listed this language as one of Iranian dialects spoken between the 9th and 13th centuries. [[Istakhri]], a medieval Iranian geographer, has written about this language, as did [[Al-Muqaddasi]], a medieval Arab geographer, who wrote "they have an obscure language and they use the phoneme ''khe'' /x/ a lot."<ref>Mehdi Marashi, Mohammad Ali Jazayery, Persian studies in North America: studies in honor of Mohammad Ali Jazayery, Ibex Publishers, Inc., 1994, {{ISBN|0-936347-35-X}}, 9780936347356, p. 269</ref> Abū Esḥāq Ṣābī had a similar report on people in the Deylam highlands who spoke a distinct language.<ref>Wilferd Madelung. Abū Isḥāq al-Ṣābī on the Alids of Tabaristān and Gīlān. Journal of Near Eastern Studies, Vol. 26, No. 1 (Jan., 1967), pp. 17-57, [[University of Chicago Press]]</ref>
According to Wilfered Madelung, in the early Islamic period the language of the Deylamites was a northwestern Iranian language. One of the characteristics of this language was an added ī sound between consonants and ā ([[Lahijan|Lāhījān]]=Līāhījān, Amīrkā=Amīrkīā).<ref>Wilferd Maelung, Deylamites [http://www.iranica.com/newsite/index.isc?Article=http://www.iranica.com/newsite/articles/unicode/v7f1/v7f123.html Encyclopedia Iranica]</ref>
