{{distinguish|Suma-Jumano language}} {{Infobox language |name= Gbeya |altname= |states=[[Central African Republic]] |speakers=ca. 250,000 |date=1996–2005 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Savanna languages|Savannas]] |fam4=[[Gbaya languages|Gbaya]] |fam5=Western |fam6=Bokoto–Bozom |lc1=gbp|ld1=Gbaya-Bossangoa |lc2=sqm|ld2=Suma |glotto=gbey1244 |glottorefname=Gbeya–Suma }}
'''Gbeya''' (''Gbɛ́yá'', Gbaya-Bossangoa) is a [[Gbaya languages|Gbaya language]] of the Central African Republic. ''Ethnologue'' reports it may be mutually intelligible with [[Bozom language|Bozom]].<ref name=samarin>{{Cite book| last = Samarin| first = William J.| title = The Gbeya language: Grammar, texts, and vocabularies| date = 1966| hdl=1807/67174|oclc=897343|asin=B000S2UYWE|url=https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/67174/1/The_Gbeya_Language.pdf}} Book reviewed in both {{cite journal|jstor=411642|title=Review of The Gbeya Language: Grammar, Texts, and Vocabularies|first=Karen|last=Courtenay|date=1 January 1968|publisher=|journal=Language|volume=44|issue=2|pages=420–423|doi=10.2307/411642|postscript=,}} and {{Cite journal|doi=10.1525/aa.1969.71.2.02a00600|title=: The Gbeya Language: Grammar, Texts, and Vocabularies . William J. Samarin|journal=American Anthropologist|volume=71|issue=2|pages=365|year=1969|last1=Crabb|first1=David W.}}</ref>
