{{about||the album by Babasónicos|Infame (album)|the TV series|Infamia (TV series)}}

In [[culture of ancient Rome|ancient Roman culture]], '''''infamia''''' (''in-'', "not," and ''fama'', "reputation") was a loss of legal or [[Social class in ancient Rome|social standing]]. As a technical term of [[Roman law]], ''infamia'' was an official exclusion from the legal protections enjoyed by a [[Roman citizen]], as imposed by a [[Roman censor|censor]] or [[praetor]].<ref>Thomas A.J. McGinn, ''Prostitution, Sexuality and the Law in Ancient Rome'' (Oxford University Press, 1998), p. 65ff.</ref> More generally, especially during the [[Roman Republic|Republic]] and [[Principate]], ''infamia'' was informal damage to one's esteem or reputation. A person who suffered ''infamia'' was an '''''infamis''''' (plural '''''infames''''').

''Infamia'' was an "inescapable consequence" for certain professionals, including [[Prostitution in ancient Rome|prostitutes and pimps]], entertainers such as [[Theatre of ancient Rome|actors]] and dancers, and [[gladiator]]s.<ref>{{cite book | author=Catharine Edwards| title=Unspeakable Professions Public Performance and Prostitution in Ancient Rome | publisher = Princeton University Press, 1997 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1ZPC3TqBZEQC&pg=PA66&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3#v=onepage&q&f=false | ISBN= 9780691011783|page= 67}}</ref> ''Infames'' could not, for instance, provide testimony in a court of law. They were liable to corporal punishment, which was usually reserved for slaves.<ref>Edwards, "Unspeakable Professions," p. 73.</ref> The ''infamia'' of entertainers did not exclude them from socializing among the Roman elite, and entertainers who were "stars", both men and women, sometimes became the lovers of such high-profile figures as the ''[[Roman dictator|dictator]]'' [[Sulla]] and [[Mark Antony]].

A [[Homosexuality in ancient Rome|passive homosexual]] who was "outed" might also be subject to social ''infamia'', though if he was a citizen he might retain his legal standing.<ref>Amy Richlin, "Not before Homosexuality: The Materiality of the ''cinaedus'' and the Roman Law against Love between Men," ''Journal of the History of Sexuality'' 3.4 (1993), pp. 550–551, 555ff.; Edwards, "Unspeakable Professions," p. 68.</ref>

The modern [[Roman Catholic Church]] has a similar concept of [[infamy]].

